From: Refracta user
Date: 2026-06-28
Subject: [PATCH v5] Learn btrfs subvolume layout from disk + NoCoW swapfile

This patch adds btrfs filesystem support to both the GUI (yad) and CLI
versions of refractainstaller, fixes EFI partition mounting, mirrors the
installer log to the target disk, and — new in v5 — makes the installer
LEARN the btrfs subvolume layout from the disk instead of hard-coding it.

Filesystem options added:

  1. "btrfs (single partition)" - formats the root partition as btrfs
     without subvolumes. Single fstab entry, no subvol= option. The
     top-level btrfs volume (subvolid=5) is mounted as /.

  2. "btrfs (with subvolumes)" - formats as btrfs, creates a set of
     subvolumes, mounts each at its mountpoint before rsync, and writes
     multiple fstab entries (all sharing one UUID with subvol= options).

Learning the layout from the disk (v5):

  The installer no longer hard-codes which subvolumes exist or where they
  mount. The disk-setup script writes a small manifest at the btrfs top
  level (subvolid=5), named ".refracta-btrfs-layout", with one TAB-separated
  "<subvolume><TAB><mountpoint>" line per subvolume. The new
  load_btrfs_layout() function:

    - mounts subvolid=5 and reads the manifest if present (authoritative),
    - otherwise discovers the existing subvolumes with `btrfs subvolume list`
      and guesses mountpoints by convention (btrfs_guess_mount),
    - sorts entries by mountpoint depth so parents mount before children,
    - derives the root subvolume (the one mapped to "/") rather than
      assuming the name "@rootfs".

  This means ANY subvolume scheme works with no edits to the installer.
  The built-in arrays remain only as a fallback for the installer's own
  "btrfs (with subvolumes)" format menu, which now also WRITES the manifest
  into the freshly-created filesystem so it can be re-learned later.

btrfs swapfile fix (v5):

  A btrfs swapfile must be NoCoW or swapon fails ("swapfile has holes").
  The swapfile is now created with chattr +C on an empty file before any
  data is written, for both plain btrfs and subvolume layouts. When the
  layout has a dedicated @swap subvolume, the swapfile is created inside it
  (kept out of root snapshots) and the fstab swap entry points at the real
  path (e.g. /swap/swapfile).

EFI boot fixes (unchanged from v4):

  - ESP mount at /target/boot/efi has error checking (check_exit).
  - mkdir -p avoids silent failure when the directory already exists.
  - The ESP is unmounted from any existing mount point before mounting.
  - install_grub() verifies the ESP is mounted before grub-install.
  - ESP mount verification uses findmnt (df does not list nested mounts).

Dual logging (unchanged from v4):

  - A background tail -F mirrors the installer error log to the target disk
    in real time; clean_log() sanitizes passwords in both copies; a final
    sync runs at the end of the install.

Changes from v4:
  - Added load_btrfs_layout() + btrfs_guess_mount(): the layout is learned
    from an on-disk manifest (or discovered), not hard-coded.
  - Root subvolume is derived from the layout instead of assuming @rootfs.
  - The format-menu path writes the manifest into the new filesystem.
  - btrfs swapfile is created NoCoW and routed into @swap when present.

Compatibility:
  - ext2/ext3/ext4 paths are unchanged; the patch only adds new branches.
  - Encryption (LUKS) is not combined with btrfs in this patch.
  - The btrfs-progs package is required. A check is performed at runtime
    with a user-friendly error message if mkfs.btrfs is missing.

Files patched:
  usr/bin/refractainstaller-yad  (GUI version, 9.6.6)
  usr/bin/refractainstaller      (CLI version, 9.6.6)

Apply with:
  patch -p1 < btrfs-support-for-refractainstaller.patch

---

--- a/usr/bin/refractainstaller-yad
+++ b/usr/bin/refractainstaller-yad
@@ -52,6 +52,86 @@
 
 configfile="/etc/refractainstaller.conf"
 
+# btrfs subvolume layout.
+#
+# The installer LEARNS the real layout from the disk instead of hard-coding it:
+# the disk-setup script writes a small manifest at the btrfs top level
+# (subvolid=5), named by $btrfs_layout_manifest, with one TAB-separated
+# "<subvolume><TAB><mountpoint>" line per subvolume. load_btrfs_layout() reads
+# it into the arrays below, so ANY subvolume scheme works with no edits here.
+#
+# The arrays below are only the FALLBACK used when no manifest is present (e.g.
+# when formatting via the installer's own "btrfs (with subvolumes)" menu).
+btrfs_layout_manifest=".refracta-btrfs-layout"
+btrfs_subvols=( @rootfs @home @var @tmp @snapshots )
+btrfs_subvol_mounts=( "/" "/home" "/var" "/tmp" "/.snapshots" )
+btrfs_root_subvol="@rootfs"   # the subvolume mounted at "/" (overridden by manifest)
+btrfs_layout_source="default" # "manifest", "guessed", or "default" (for messages)
+
+# btrfs_guess_mount SUBVOL
+#   Best-effort mountpoint for a subvolume name when no manifest exists.
+#   Known names are mapped explicitly; unknown "@a_b_c" become "/a/b/c".
+btrfs_guess_mount () {
+	case "$1" in
+		@rootfs|@root|@)  echo "/" ;;
+		@home)            echo "/home" ;;
+		@snapshots)       echo "/.snapshots" ;;
+		@swap)            echo "/swap" ;;
+		@var)             echo "/var" ;;
+		@var_log)         echo "/var/log" ;;
+		@var_cache)       echo "/var/cache" ;;
+		@libvirt_images)  echo "/var/lib/libvirt/images" ;;
+		@tmp)             echo "/tmp" ;;
+		@opt)             echo "/opt" ;;
+		@srv)             echo "/srv" ;;
+		@*)               local _n="${1#@}" ; echo "/${_n//_//}" ;;
+		*)                echo "" ;;
+	esac
+}
+
+# load_btrfs_layout DEVICE
+#   Learn the btrfs subvolume layout of DEVICE by mounting its top level
+#   (subvolid=5) and either (1) reading the layout manifest if present
+#   (authoritative), or (2) discovering the existing subvolumes with
+#   `btrfs subvolume list` and guessing their mountpoints by convention.
+#   Populates btrfs_subvols / btrfs_subvol_mounts (sorted shallow-first so
+#   parent mounts precede children) and btrfs_root_subvol / btrfs_layout_source.
+#   Returns 0 if any subvolumes were found (=> subvol mode), 1 otherwise.
+load_btrfs_layout () {
+	local _dev="$1" _tmp _raw="" _src="default" _rc=1 _sv _mp _i
+	_tmp=$(mktemp -d)
+	mount -o subvolid=5 "$_dev" "$_tmp" 2>/dev/null || { rmdir "$_tmp"; return 1; }
+	if [[ -f "$_tmp/$btrfs_layout_manifest" ]]; then
+		_raw=$(awk -F'\t' '/^[[:space:]]*#/{next} NF<2{next} {print $1"\t"$2}' "$_tmp/$btrfs_layout_manifest")
+		_src="manifest"
+	else
+		_raw=$(btrfs subvolume list "$_tmp" 2>/dev/null | awk '{print $NF}' \
+			| while read -r _s; do
+				[[ "$_s" == */* ]] && continue   # skip nested subvolumes
+				printf '%s\t%s\n' "$_s" "$(btrfs_guess_mount "$_s")"
+			done)
+		_src="guessed"
+	fi
+	umount "$_tmp" 2>/dev/null; rmdir "$_tmp"
+
+	if [[ -n "$_raw" ]]; then
+		btrfs_subvols=(); btrfs_subvol_mounts=()
+		while IFS=$'\t' read -r _ _sv _mp; do
+			[[ -z "$_sv" || -z "$_mp" ]] && continue
+			btrfs_subvols+=("$_sv"); btrfs_subvol_mounts+=("$_mp")
+		done < <(printf '%s\n' "$_raw" | awk -F'\t' 'NF>=2 && $2!="" {d=gsub(/\//,"/",$2); print d"\t"$1"\t"$2}' | sort -n -k1,1)
+		if [[ ${#btrfs_subvols[@]} -gt 0 ]]; then
+			btrfs_root_subvol="@rootfs"
+			for _i in "${!btrfs_subvols[@]}"; do
+				[[ "${btrfs_subvol_mounts[$_i]}" == "/" ]] && btrfs_root_subvol="${btrfs_subvols[$_i]}"
+			done
+			btrfs_layout_source="$_src"
+			_rc=0
+		fi
+	fi
+	return $_rc
+}
+
